      "rationale": "All production simulations converged with force residual norms below 1e-4. Automatic time-stepping was enabled with a minimum substep of 1/500 of total load. No solver warnings or unconverged substeps were recorded across all 11 matched simulation instances."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup by second analyst; checklist-based verification of boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions.",
      "rationale": "A second qualified analyst independently reviewed all model setup files against a pre-defined checklist covering boundary conditions (fixed inferior vertebral body, axial compressive load at superior body), material property assignments (Ti-6Al-4V: E=114 GPa, yield 880 MPa), and contact pair definitions. No discrepancies were identified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum elastoplastic constitutive model with isotropic hardening validated for Ti-6Al-4V implant-grade material; contact mechanics formulation appropriate for threaded interfaces.",
      "rationale": "The bilinear isotropic hardening model is well-established for Ti-6Al-4V under quasi-static loading. Augmented Lagrangian contact with friction coefficient 0.2 at screw-rod interface reflects published literature for dry titanium-on-titanium contact. Vertebral body surrogate (UHMWPE block) modeled as linear elastic (E=1.17 GPa) consistent with ASTM F1717 standardized test block properties."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified material test reports for the production lot; geometric dimensions from CMM measurement of test articles.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties (elastic modulus, yield strength, tangent modulus) were obtained from certified material test reports for the specific production lot used in bench testing. Screw and rod geometry was characterized by coordinate measuring machine (CMM) on three randomly selected test articles; mean dimensions used in the model with variability documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test constructs from production-representative hardware; constructs assembled per surgical technique guide by trained personnel.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (n=6 Lab A, n=5 Lab B). All hardware was drawn from the same production lot as the CMM-characterized samples. Assembly was performed by personnel trained to the surgical technique guide, consistent with clinical use conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios including at least two load levels and two construct configurations.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 standardized load configuration (static compression-bending, 10 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient conditions). Only one test condition was evaluated, which is insufficient to span the full clinical loading envelope. This factor is assessed below the required level; the gap is acknowledged and accepted given that ASTM F1717 is the regulatory standard for this device class and the model risk level does not mandate multi-condition validation for this submission."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions, loading) traceable to as-tested experimental conditions; any deviations documented and sensitivity-analyzed.",
      "rationale": "All simulation inputs were reconciled to as-tested experimental conditions. Screw torque preload was converted to an equivalent contact pressure via an analytical thread mechanics model and validated against measured clamp-force data. UHMWPE block stiffness was confirmed against independent coupon tests. No unresolved input equivalency gaps were identified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 and percent difference < 10% for all three primary QoIs; uncertainty quantification accounts for both experimental measurement uncertainty and model parameter uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) satisfy both acceptance criteria. E/uval values of 0.81, 1.42, and 0.63 are all below 1.96. Percent differences of 4.2%, 6.7%, and 3.1% are all below 10%. Experimental uncertainty was propagated from load cell calibration (±0.5% FS) and displacement transducer (±0.1 mm). Model parameter uncertainty was estimated via one-at-a-time sensitivity analysis on material properties."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) directly correspond to the regulatory submission endpoints specified in FDA guidance for spinal pedicle screws.",
      "rationale": "The three selected QoIs map directly to the performance endpoints required by FDA guidance for 510(k) submissions for spinal pedicle screw systems. Construct stiffness and yield force are primary structural safety indicators; force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield behavior relevant to fatigue life estimation. The QoIs are clinically meaningful and regulatorily required."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities performed on the same device design, same material lot, same loading modality, and same test standard as the intended regulatory submission.",
      "rationale": "The validation activities are directly relevant to the COU. The validated model uses the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry, the same Ti-6Al-4V production lot, and the same ASTM F1717 test configuration as the intended regulatory submission. The two-laboratory design strengthens inter-laboratory reproducibility evidence. The only noted gap (single test condition) is documented under the Test conditions factor."
